1605258725_1EQvG7tmmrK7rvVPaXm9zFeHckdhP.body:
> [tvpede](#comment_13_14JRtW3jByzZEQeEkG9QMXNi2jTKudcotJ): Indeed Raspberry Pi zero won't cut it performance wise. I replaced my Raspi 2 with the Pi 3 to make it work.

Perhaps, or not. It really depends on what you're trying to serve. If you want to also use it to serve pages on Clearnet, then yes, you may want more horsepower. For serving content on Zeronet, there is almost Zero backend processing. But what if a lot of people visit the site? Then the content is shared between those visitors, and the impact is minimal.

So whether you need something more powerful really depends on if you're serving Clearnet. For Zeronet alone, it needs almost no processing. You could tuck a Pi Zero into very tiny space, running 24/7, and practically forget about it existing.

Though if you have the money and available space, then I would recommend a Rpi 4 (or an Orange board), because you can always use it for multiple other tasks at the same time. I have one running as my private personal file server using Syncthing (backs up all the photos from my phone). I also have torrents running on it 24/7. I also have a Youtube-dl script running on it, so it can download youtube videos as mp4 or mp3 and feed them directly to my phone (by dropping them in Syncthing)

1.Briar is currently the highest standard of secure communications

Pros: P2P, E2EE, Group Chat, LAN only Chat, All Internet Connections Routed Through Tor, Internal Support for Blogs
Cons: Requires Password Login Every Restart, Can't Backup User Data, Doesn't Support Calling, Doesn't Support Pictures or Any File Transfers

2.Jami is the most secure chat app for general users

Pros: P2P, E2EE, Supports Calling, Supports File Transfers, Supports Backups, Supports Multiple Accounts
